rived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Niccolo da Carrara was born in 1280, in Padova, Veneto, Italy as the son of Jacopo de Carrara. He had at least 2 sons with Figlia di Uguccione di Carturo. He died in 1340, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1280–1340":"1280–1340","1242–Female":"1242–Surnud","1264–1324":"1264–1324","1207–1242":"1207–1242","1324":"1324","22 November 1324":"22. november 1324","1264":"1264","1242":"1242","1340":"1340","1280":"1280","1207":"1207","Padua, Veneto, Italy":"Padova, Veneto, Itaalia","Padova, Veneto, Italy":"Padova, Veneto, Itaalia","San Stefano Abbey, Carrara, Massa-Carrara, Tuscany, Italy":"Carrara, Massa-Carrara, Toscana, Itaalia"},"fi":{"1280–1340":"1280–1340","1242–Female":"1242–Kuollut","1264–1324":"1264–1324","1207–1242":"1207–1242","1324":"1324","22 November 1324":"22. marraskuuta 1324","1264":"1264","1242":"1242","1340":"1340","1280":"1280","1207":"1207","Padua, Veneto, Italy":"Padova, Veneto, Italia","Padova, Veneto, Italy":"Padova, Veneto, Italia","San Stefano Abbey, Carrara, Massa-Carrara, Tuscany, 